": "ATP", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9049633145332336, "span": {"begin": 693, "end": 696}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:4712"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "CI", "obj": "gene", "prob": null, "span": {"begin": 759, "end": 761}}, {"id": ["CHEBI:30616"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "ATP", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9528745412826538, "span": {"begin": 814, "end": 817}}, {"id": ["mesh:D028361"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "mitochondrial dysfunction", "obj": "disease", "prob": 0.9982590079307556, "span": {"begin": 873, "end": 898}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:4712"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "CI", "obj": "gene", "prob": null, "span": {"begin": 903, "end": 905}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "synaptic mitochondria", "obj": "cell_type", "prob": 0.5155371427536011, "span": {"begin": 964, "end": 985}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "non-synaptic mitochondria", "obj": "cell_type", "prob": 0.5863617658615112, "span": {"begin": 994, "end": 1019}}, {"id": ["mim:168600"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "PD", "obj": "disease", "prob": null, "span": {"begin": 1098, "end": 1100}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:4712"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "CI", "obj": "gene", "prob": null, "span": {"begin": 1146, "end": 1148}}, {"id": ["mesh:D010100"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "oxygen", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9955101013183594, "span": {"begin": 1214, "end": 1220}}, {"id": ["mesh:D013481"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "superoxide", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9997099041938782, "span": {"begin": 1274, "end": 1284}}, {"id": ["mesh:D006861"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "hydrogen peroxide", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9997931718826294, "span": {"begin": 1317, "end": 1334}}, {"id": ["mesh:D003681"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "oxidative stress", "obj": "disease", "prob": 0.8787156343460083, "span": {"begin": 1367, "end": 1383}}], "text": "The weight of evidence supporting the relationship between binding of an inhibitor to NADH-ubiquinone oxidoreducatse and its inhibition is strong.  Biological Plausibility  There is an extensive understanding of the functional relationship between binding of an inhibitor to NADH-ubiquinone oxidoreductase (CI) and its inhibition. As the first entry complex of mitochondrial respiratory chain, CI oxidizes NADH and transfers electrons via a flavin mononucleotide cofactor and several Fe-S complexes to ubiquinone. The electron flow is coupled to the translocation of protons from the matrix to the intermembrane space. This helps to establish the electrochemical gradient that is used to fuel ATP synthesis (Greenamyre et al., 2001). If an inhibitor binds to CI, the electron transfer is blocked. This compromises ATP synthesis and maintenance of &Delta;&psi;m, leading to mitochondrial dysfunction. As CI exerts a higher control over oxidative phosphorylation in synaptic mitochondria than in non-synaptic mitochondria in the brain (Davey and Clark, 1996), specific functional defects observed in PD may be explained. It is well documented that CI inhibition is one of the main sites at which electron leakage to oxygen occurs. This results in a production of ROS, such as superoxide (Efremov and Sazanow, 2011) and hydrogen peroxide, which are main contributors to oxidative stress (Greenamyre et al., 2001).", "timestamp": "Mon Jun 08 14:16:49 +0000 2026"}